{{Distinguish|Philosophy of language}}
'''Linguistic philosophy''' is the view that philosophical problems are problems which may be solved (or dissolved) either by reforming language, or by understanding more about the language we presently use.<ref>Rorty 1967, page 3.</ref> The former position is that of ideal language philosophy, the latter the position of [[ordinary language philosophy]].<ref>Rorty 1967.</ref>

