[[Category:Natural language processing]] [[Category:Neuropsychological assessment]] [[Category:Language]] [[Category:Philosophical logic]] [[Category:Philosophy of language]]

In [[linguistics]], the term '''near-native speakers''' is used for people who are "highly proficient speakers who are distinguishable from native speakers, but only in small ways."<ref name="Gass&Glew">{{cite book|last1=Gass|first1=Susan|last2=Glew|first2=Margo|editor1-last=Altarriba|editor1-first=Jeanette|editor2-last=Heredia|editor2-first=Roberto R.|title=An Introduction to Bilingualism: Principles and Processes|chapter=Second Language Acquisition and Bilingualism|date=2008|publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]]|isbn=9780805851342|pages=[https://books.google.am/books?id=Kt-EMiXPa40C&pg=PA267&dq=Near-Native+Speaker 267–268]}}</ref> Analysis of native and near-native speakers indicates that they differ in their underlying grammar and intuition, meaning that they do not interpret grammatical contrasts the same way. However, this divergence typically does not impact a near-native speaker's regular usage of the language.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Coppieters|first=René|date=1987-01-01|title=Competence Differences between Native and Near-Native Speakers|jstor=415005|journal=Language|volume=63|issue=3|pages=544–573|doi=10.2307/415005}}</ref>

